Introduction to Deque in Java

Deque (Double-Ended Queue) is an interface in Java that allows adding and removing elements from both ends.

👉 This means:

you can work like a queue (FIFO)
or like a stack (LIFO)
Key Idea
Front ← [ elements ] → Back

👉 You can add/remove from:

front
back
Common Implementations
ArrayDeque → most used (fast, modern)
LinkedList → also supports Deque
ArrayDeque in Java

ArrayDeque is a class that implements Deque.

👉 It is based on a resizable array and is:

faster than Stack
faster than LinkedList (in most cases)
Creating an ArrayDeque
import java.util.ArrayDeque;
import java.util.Deque;

Deque<String> deque = new ArrayDeque<>();
Adding Elements
deque.addFirst("A"); // front
deque.addLast("B");  // back

deque.offerFirst("C");
deque.offerLast("D");
Removing Elements
deque.removeFirst();
deque.removeLast();

deque.pollFirst();
deque.pollLast();
Accessing Elements
deque.peekFirst();
deque.peekLast();
Using as Stack (LIFO)
deque.push("A");
deque.push("B");

deque.pop(); // B
Using as Queue (FIFO)
deque.offer("A");
deque.offer("B");

deque.poll(); // A
Important Features
works as both stack and queue
does NOT allow null ❌
not thread-safe
very fast
Performance
Operation	Complexity
add/remove	O(1)
access ends	O(1)
ArrayDeque vs LinkedList
Feature	ArrayDeque	LinkedList
Performance	Faster	Slower
Memory	Less	More
Usage	Preferred	Less common
When to use ArrayDeque

Use it when:

you need stack or queue behavior
performance matters
modern Java approach
Summary
Deque allows operations on both ends
ArrayDeque is the best general-purpose implementation
can be used as stack or queue
fast and efficient
